data:
Title: INTEGRATION OF GOOD PRAXIS FOR EUROPEAN MUSICAL LYCEUMS 
Acronym: EUGYMUS - EUROPA GYMNASIUM MUSICAE

Summary

The Eugymus Project is for 15 beneficiaries from the sending organisation Liceo Scientifico e Musicale G. Marconi of Pesaro. The beneficiaries are mainly Directors, Administration Staff, teachers and trainers of the sending organisation.

Considering the recent institution of Musical Lyceums (2010-2011) and its new innovative training structure, it is necessary to compare the school and university systems in Europe in order to: 

 Acquire a major comprehension of ways and polices of education and training systems in  the musical sector among European Countries;
 Create changes in order to balance European training paths;
 International connection for Italian Schools and for the Italian education system; 
 Improve the quality of the work place and of the activities of the students;
 Increase professional and career development of our teachers;
 Increase the knowledge of foreign languages; 
 Promote major motivation and satisfaction with work related daily tasks. 

The areas of improvement which mainly interest the net of partners are mainly:
 Organisation in order to enhance quality; 
 Management competences; 
 Staff competencies; 
 Methods of teaching in Europe;
 Language competences;
 Organisation of training, teaching and learning; 
  Relationship with local communities.  

Specific Objectives of Eugymus Project are: 
 
- Broaden one’s knowledge and comprehension of policies and national/international procedures;
- Foster the definition of a professional training in the musical sector, shared at the European level;
- Define the common criteria for the definition of professionalism in order to select teaching staff;
- Create changes in order to update and internationalize the Musical Lyceums;
- Connection between formal and non-formal learning, professional training to prepare for the work place;
- Strengthen the quality of teaching and of learning;
- Promote a training path in order to create an European Curriculum for the European Musical Lyceum;
- Create a Final Report of good praxis to spread through the portal and through all national and European institutions in the musical sector.

The Eugymus project develops those issues and problems that Musical Lyceums are facing nowadays and these are mainly: 

1. Finding suitable teaching staff; 
2. Planning and Organization of classes’ timetables;
3. Employment chances. 

The main aim of the sending organisation is to create a lasting partnership with other training providers having similar curricula and being compatible in terms of teaching and learning with the Musical Lyceums. 
The project will help the school to put into practice the experience acquired by the participants, through benchmarking and through the exchange of good practises. 
Receiving partner are schools, public and private bodies of the following countries: Denmark, Germany, Hungary and the United Kingdom and their expertise will be of high value as they have developed already knowledge and skills in the musical training of other European students of the same age range of the students of the Liceo Marconi and they can support and advice the sending organisation with what relates to the 3 main area of interest: 

1) Management of Training
2) Methods Use and implemented for training
3) Selection and employment of qualified teaching staff and trainers. 

The project will last one year and the main activities are: 

1.Preparatory Activity: 
This is about the language and cultural preparation. Training activities will involve all staff: Directors, Administration Staff, teachers and trainers. 

2. Activity for Professional Development: 

Job shadowing/observe for 2 week time the colleagues working in foreign institutes/schools. 
These will be the activities carried out: 

- Job Shadowing Activity;  
- Exchange of professional experience with foreign colleagues; 
- Acquisition of new strategies of teaching, evaluation, organisation and management;
- Meeting with local communities to exchange cultural ideas about the music sector, this will include meeting with in orchestras, choirs, theatres, Concerts, Musical bands. 

3. Follow up

Impact
The project shall impact over the following: 
• Quality of Teaching; 
• Learning of Students; 
• Ways of selecting teaching staff; 
• Management of classes’ timetables; 
• Creation of School Curriculum which may be aligned with the training in Europe in the musical sector.

Dissemination of results: 
Through the portal of the national net of Musical Lyceums: http://www.liceimusicalicoreutici.org/
Realization of a Report of good praxis. 

Evaluation 
This will be strictly related to the objectives fulfilled.

Context / background of project

The Comprehensive School " Giuseppe Lombardo Radice " is located in the new city centre of Syracuse,   in a busy neighborhood with  a large number  of schools, offices and commercial activities . The Institute is made up of 40 classes for a total of 972 students, divided into 202 pupils in Kindergarten, 520 attend  Primary school, whereas  250  attend Secondary school .

The mission of the school can be summarized as follows :

1 . A school that is  willing to talk and exchange information  with students , families, and  the territory ;

2 . Encourage awareness as regards  respecting and  accepting others ;

3 . Encourage the development of skills and competences to help students make appropriate choices 



Objectives of our project ;



 Socialize and disseminate initiatives, projects ,important  experiences, to promote the European dimension in education ;

 Identify good practices and develop extensible intervention models ;

 Propose strategies and models of intervention for the promotion of inter- transcultural education ;

 Encourage the development of common policies regarding the integration of foreign students in our school ;

 Identify forms of exchange between  teaching staff and, if possible,  students.

Discuss the planning regarding  Action Ka2 ( former Comenius)

 Investigate and learn about the educational systems in the host countries .



Number and profile of Participants



The training needs of teachers relate primarily to the new methods and new tools for teaching , the knowledge of the European dimension in education , and the enhancement  of  language skills .

The participants include  12 secondary school teachers  , 6 from primary school  and  4 from kindergarten . The Head Teacher and the school secretary also  take part in the project. English language  teachers  will be  available to guide and support delegations and  other colleagues in their needs. In addition , our school has provided for the inclusion of supply teachers working on short-term contracts, to participate  in the training programme too, as they would otherwise  be excluded from any training .

Description of activities

An activity plan has been drawn up, of which the details will be defined with the headmasters and the contact teachers of the schools in the future; the plan is subdivided as follows:

1. School visit and presentation of the Italian delegation;

2. Knowledge of the education system of the host countries;

3. Discussion about the learning methodology of foreign students' national language, also via TIC;

4. Evaluation methodologies of acquired learning;



Special attention should be applied to the following points:

• classroom observation, above all in the starting and finishing classes;

• inclusion of foreign students: case studies;

• acquisition of new teaching and evaluation strategies;

• studies of recovery models and evaluation sheets;

• setting up of a strategic partnership KA2 (ex Comenius).



Methodology to be used in carrying out the project



The training abroad program will follow established methodological criteria. It shall be carried out according to the job-shadowing methods, with moments of observation; teaching in the host country's language; exchanges of experiences with foreign colleagues; acquisition of new teaching and evaluation strategies, etc.

Job-shadowing is an occasion to provide skills, techniques and methods of concrete application for participants in the educational activities and to favor the exchanges of experiences and good teaching practices. Furthermore the use of the foreign languages will be stimulated, meanwhile teamworks, collaboration amongst teachers from different countries will contribute to concretely acting out the desired European dimension.  



A short description of the results and impact envisaged

In synthesis, we can summarise the desired results:

For teachers

• to improve the personal linguistic, social and intercultural skills and capabilities

• to acquire, develop and transmit abilities in specific areas



For school

• to disseminate and socialize the acquired skills

• reinforcement of the European prospect



The potential longer term benefits

From the emotional point of view, it is intended to give a strong response to a diffuse state of apathy present in the category as regards the inadequate institutional role attributed/recognized to the teaching profession (unsatisfactory salary, lack of consideration on the part of public opinion, etc.). The comparison with experiences and methods, which comes from social realities, the possibility of entwining meetings and public relationships, the feeling of belonging to a new dimension of teaching will enable the school and the teachers envolved in the project to enrich the personal and professional experience.

The legislative framework and educational observations give the school autonomy, the role of a permanently guiding agency, targeting in its senior management the implementation of active job seeking and work placement policies. In effect, its role is, above all, to deliver core training of a technical and professional nature, which is of particular importance for today's world of work (and already in place at the school thanks, above all, to the work placement training programme), transferable skills, life skills: group working, effective communication, cooperation.
In line with the aims of the national "Garanzia Giovani" programme, of increasing employment and employability for youngsters, the school's training program and the associated guidance activities for school leavers fulfil a critically important role, alongside the hard skills learned in the classroom. Indeed, through training and other experiences from interacting with the world of work, it is possible to conduct trials and to validate the development and acquisition of the skills needed to enter the workforce, by optimising the concept - as the European Union has called for on several occasions - of skills as applied knowledge, in action.
From this point of view, the "real world tasks", which companies devise with the school's representatives and assign to the students, play a central role. In the real world tasks, which are tangible and challenging workplace scenarios, the school's representatives identify with representatives of the companies training links and synergies with the school curriculum, thereby creating the conditions for an effective validation of the training programme, measured in terms of knowledge acquired.
To this end, three of the key competences for citizenship proposed by the European Union are used as reference:
• learning to learn: ability to organise one's own learning;
• sense of initiative and entrepreneurship;
• social and civic competences.
In short, training experience and guidance initiatives occupy an essential place within the school's education offer, underpinning a number of key aspects:
• in relation to employability, analysis and management of performance in a pro-active and problem-solving approach, as part of a virtuous cycle with the skills acquired in the classroom;
• as an opportunity for meta-reflection and self-assessment, highlighting overlaps between technical and professional knowledge and life skills linked to active citizenship;
• in the personal pathway to actively seeking work.
To ensure that the school's guidance and work placement policies are sustainable, lasting and effective, we are applying for this project to grow the number of guidance teachers, the school's future career team, which, as part of a plan of work shadowing abroad, develops and refines the following professional competences, to be spent in the actions/steps/phases of guidance for school leavers:
- analysis of the demand in terms of expectations and requests from students leaving the school;
- definition of a skills assessment, using the tools made available by the AlmaDiploma programme and others which will be acquired as part of the experience of work shadowing abroad;
- ensuring the transparency of the student's "training record" by building on experiences and skills acquired in non-formal, informal and formal contexts;
- creating, to match demand and emerging skills, a personal career plan towards university or the workplace;
- preparation, monitoring and final reporting of experiences from the work placements organised by the school in collaboration with the host companies; 
- career tracking for one or two years from finishing school;
- longer-term: redefinition of the active pathways curriculum at the Martini school, using transferable skills profiles connected to the professional profiles of school leavers.
The bidders are the 15 teachers who are currently involved in the guidance activities, for both new admissions and leavers; they include various different key individuals in the school: staff, holding instrumental roles, responsible for activities relating to the development of the informal and non-formal student curriculum, vocational career plans, relationships with universities and with the world of work.
The teachers, using the active learning "by doing" methodology, will support colleagues who have proven experience in a European context and with this far-reaching and active approach they will instil the following in the school and the network of schools in the Rotaliana area, of which the Martini school is part: seminars, workshops, discussions and above all the spreading of best practice within the school, between colleagues who will be key to the growth of the project's results.
